subsection.p:
The exponents of a polynomial can only be non-negative integers. That means functions like
          y = x^\frac{1}{2}
          and
          y = 2x^3 - x^{-5}
        are not polynomials.

image.latex-image-code:

\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ ,
  ymax=300, ymin=-300,
  xmax=4, xmin=-5,
  xlabel=$x$,ylabel=$f(x)$ ]
  \addplot[smooth, blue,
  domain=-5:4]
  {8*x^3+4*x^2-100*x+48};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

subsection.p:
In Chapter, we learned to shift a parabola left or right, just by adding a number to the input: 
          y = (x+4)^2 \amp\text{ is the parabola }x^2\text{, moved to the left by }4 \text{ units}
          y = (x-3)^2 \amp\text{ is the parabola }x^2\text{, moved to the right by }3 \text{ units}

image.latex-image-code:

\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ ,
  ymax=40, ymin=-40,
  xmax=6, xmin=-6,
  xlabel=$x$,ylabel=$y$ ]
  \addplot[smooth, blue,
  domain=-5:4]
  {(x+3)^2*(x-1)};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
